        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Brandon | Suff.</placeName>
                    <date>Mar. 17. 1878.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir—</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I beg to thank you most deeply for your present of The Origin of Species, which came yesterday.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I look upon it as the greatest honour that has fallen to me, and shall use your sympathy and congratulations as a panacea for all the harsh criticisms that may be in store for me.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Sincerely trusting your health is better—</p>
<p>I am, My dear Sir | Yours very gratefully | Sydney B. J. Skertchly <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">C. Darwin, Esq. F.R.S.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
            
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">Skertchly had asked for a copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11395.xml">letter of 4 March 1878</ref>.</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11394.xml">letter to S. B. J. Skertchly, 2 March 1878</ref>. Skertchly’s forthcoming publication contained a discussion of the age and divisions of the Palaeolithic period (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10236.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Skertchly 1879</ref>, pp. 65–9).</note>
            </div>   
       
